content.description:
Easy climbing to the top of the ledge to the dihedral.  Stem the off width crack to the chains on smooth and friendly features. You can elect to take this route to the top if you desire. The moves right above the chains are a bit awkward and sharp.  Angle left to the bolt on the ramp for Deez Nuts and continue to the 5.9  top section.

The top 15 feet has a solid 5.9 move right before the chains and is out of sight of your belayer. There is a bolt at your waist to protect the move but too much slack and a soft catch may land you on the ledge.
content.location: Large dihedral with an off width crack starting behind large boulder that looks cool to climb but isn't.

content.description: A very obvious S curve arete.  I have never led this route.  I did it on TR when I drilled it but for some reason I never came back and led it.  I have a feeling I botched the bolt placements so climb this one at your own risk and then let me know. Also, it looks sharp!
content.location: The Gin and Juice arete is very obvious.

content.description:
1. Deez Nuts - Start on the left in a crack under an overhang,  stem the dihedral to a ledge. The crux is pulling through the small roof off of the ledge.  Then enjoy caressing the silky smooth chert nodule nut sack like knobs that allow you to float above the sharpness to the chains. You can continue on past the chains if you want to.  The steep moves above the chains are fun with really solid jugs that are a bit sharp. There is a big ramp that leads to a ledge.  The top 15 feet has a solid 5.9 move right before the chains and is out of sight of your belayer. There is a bolt at your waist to protect the move but too much slack and a soft catch may land you on the ledge.

TR Variation - Start on an arete and work into the crack that angles right and joins the dihedral for "Mom's Spaghetti".  This route is very sharp and awkward through the crack.
content.location: Look for the upside down Y crack behind a large boulder that looks like it would be fun to climb.  (It's not).

content.description: This is one of the better routes at the Gulch. Steep exposed climbing, through three bulbous "bits", with the largest & most overhung, "bit", being at the top. The technical crux is at the first bolt.  There is an access anchor at the top that will allow you to easily gain the cold shuts for a TR.
content.protection: Bolts - Chains - Lowering Carabiners (Please don't steal them)
content.location: Just to the right of the large sweet looking boulder up on the second tier.  The boulder is very sharp and not sweet.

content.description: This route is really fun. The route has been scrubbed clean by water and the holds are more supple than any other easy route at the gulch. Start by laybacking the crisp wide off width crack using positive feet on the left wall to a ledge.  Enjoy fun stem moves up to the terminus of the wide crack and then commit to the large edge out right. Climb positive water polished chert nodules to the chains. It's more fun if you commit to the face and resist the urge to go to the left on the final 15 feet.
content.location: Very large and prominent dihedral with a large 8 inch crisp crack at the start.
